@node Intro Introduction

Introduction

IndexAG is a program I wrote after I got the idea from an ARexx book I was learning from.
It will read an AmigaGuide document and make an index of its words and/or links in a context
form.

It allows to setup certain parameters to control the way the index is made such as excluding
certain words, setting a maximum to the number of times a word appears in a node, recognizing
word groups and to make an index with words or links only.

To see an example, check out the index of this document (after a bit of editing, of course).

This program is freeware, and can be distributed provided the archive is not altered.

IndexAG is ©1998 Sébastien Boisvert.

Part of the code (List sorting routine) is ©1996 Heinz Wrobel. My thanks to him for posting
the algorithm on the newsgroup - it saved me some headaches!.


Version History

1.0   Initial release

1.1   Bug fix - couldn't find default word file

2.0   Written in C (speed!)
      There's no longer a need for a seperate 'masterfile' and sorted 'wordfile'

@endnode

@node installation "Installation and requirements"

Installation & Requirements

Installation is straightforward: simply copy the file 'IndexAG' and 'IndexAG.words'
together in a directory.

@endnode

@node Usage "Usage for this program" 

Usage

The program take the following AmigaDOS style arguments (enter 'IndexAG ?' to see arguments):

FILENAME   this is a required argument; it is the filename for the AmigaGuide file to scan

WORDFILE   optional, defaults to the included 'IndexAG.words' file. This is used to specify
           an alternate list of words to exclude
           
THRESHOLD  repeat threshold - the maximum number of times a word can be repeated in any one
           node before it is considered too repetitive and excluded for that node; defaults 
           to 10

NOWORDS    this switch specifies that only links should be indexed

NOLINKS    this switch specifies that only words should be indexed. Mutually exclusive with
           NOWORDS and will overide NOWORDS.

COMMENT    this switch works in conjunction with THRESHOLD and will 'comment' (put a '*' in
           front of) a link in the index for which the word exceeds the threshold. This allows
           you to see that the word is repetitive and let you decide if you want to keep it.

GROUPSTART this specifies the character sequence that determines the start of a word group
           (see below); defaults to '<'

GROUPEND   this specifies the character sequence that determines the end of a word group
           (see below); defaults to '>'


'Word groups' are words that are enclosed within a start and end sequence which will be indexed
together. For example, if you wanted to have everyting that is set in @{b}Bold@{ub} in the 
document to be grouped together, you would set the variables this way:

GROUPSTART \@{b}
GROUPEND \@{ub}   (the detection will be case insensitive)

and this will group "\@{b}This is a word group\@{ub}" as the link 'This is a word group'. Please
note that the start and end sequences should appear on the same line in the document file, and
should not contain any spaces.
        
If you don't want to change the appearance of the text, you can also use a unique sequence
and strip it out of your document with your word editor after you've done the index. You could
also use a backslash (\\), which does not alter the appearance when displayed.

The index node is output as the file 'index.node' in the current directory.

           
Example usages:

  IndexAG amigaguide.guide THRESHOLD 20 NOLINKS
  
     will scan 'amigaguide.guide' and set the repeat threshold to 20 and not index links
     
  IndexAG amigaguide.guide WORDFILE alternate COMMENT GROUPSTART <= GROUPEND =>
  
     will scan 'amigaguide.guide', use 'alternate' as the word list, comment word links 
     which exceeds the default threshold and set GROUPSTART/END to '<=' and '=>' respectively.

@endnode

@node Notes "Notes and Tips"

Notes

About the IndexAG.words file

This file  contains the words that are to be excluded from the index. The file contains the words listed 
in 2 groups: Computer related words at the begining, and more common words at the end. This is the file 
you should use if you want to add new words to be excluded as they are listed in a logical manner.

The format for the file is one word per line, and lines beginning with a semi-colon (;) are considered 
comments and ignored.


General notes about the program:

The program is smart enough to detect the full names of nodes/liks and their titles with or without
quotes, and able to recognize any linenumber references for node links.
(example '\@{"Foo" link "bar" 10}' will create a link called "Foo" to node "bar" at line 10 in that node.)

If a node cannot be found for a link, a warning with the link name will be displayed while creating
the index and a "?" will be place in front of the link. Double check your links to make sure they're
correct. (This may happen if you have an external link).

Command sequences (such as \@ENDNODE,\@TITLE) are skipped during scanning

Functions sequences (such as \@{b},\@{ub}) are striped out, but the words within them are still scanned. 
The program checks for word group sequences before striping out functions.

Words appearing in word groups and in the word list to exclude will not be excluded.

Special characters (non alphanumeric) are striped out. Periods, hyphens, apostrophes slashes and underscores 
(.-'_/\) are striped out only if at beginning/end of a word.

The program DOES NOT attempt to remove plural forms or contractions in words.

Words are indexed to the node they belong to, along with the line number of the first occurence in the node.
Since the index is a context index, you'll see a word link for each node of the document in which it appears,
so don't be suprised if you see the same word twice or more; that means it appears in more than one node.

Internal links are indexed to the node they point to.

External links (such as \@{"foo" SYSTEM "bar"}) are indexed like words: back to the node they belong to.

The program is case insensitive for group sequences and links; eg:"\@{ub}" will be considered the same 
as "\@{UB}".

The program cannot accept line that are greater than 512 characters.

Tips

Think about how you want to write the document, and what you'd like to see in the index. If you want
word groups, determine what character sequence you want to use and use it throughout. Remember to 
match a start sequence with an end sequence on the same line in the file, and that a space should appear
before a start sequence and after an end sequence.

Follow the AmigaGuide guidelines. Write properly: a space before any '@' is VERY important (except commands!);
put a space after punctuation marks (periods, colons, etc...)


You WILL need to edit the final output. No matter how well you configure the program, there will 
always be things that 'just don't belong there' (this will also depend on your writing style). You may need 
to run the program a few times, maybe adding a few words in the list along the way. There will probably be 
comment lines you'll need to consider, if any. This program will help make the context index, but not a perfect
one!


Possible Future enhancements:


Make it smarter(?) My first idea was to include the possibility to recognise
words that are often grouped together, without the need for start/end sequences;
however, this might be too complex and slow it down. I'll have to consider it.

Maybe create a GUI for it, if there is a demand (or I feel like doing it)

Any suggestions you have I'll consider...

@endnode

